<div id="review_2478506765" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2478506765" />
    <a title="Ilana" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/59371159-ilana"><img alt="Ilana" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1615453224p2/59371159.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2478506765?book_show_action=true">Jun 28, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ilana" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ilana" href="/user/show/59371159-ilana">Ilana</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audible Audio " href="/book/show/25784171-beauty-and-sadness">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59371159-ilana?shelf=nobel-prize">nobel-prize</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59371159-ilana?shelf=japan">japan</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59371159-ilana?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59371159-ilana?shelf=literature">literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59371159-ilana?shelf=audiobooks">audiobooks</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59371159-ilana?shelf=20th-century">20th-century</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59371159-ilana?shelf=guardian-1000">guardian-1000</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2478506765" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10420663177864437147">Some 25 years after Toshio Oki&apos;s affair with then fifteen-year-old Otoko Ueno, Toshio, feeling nostalgic, decides to visit a now mature Otoko to listen to the ringing of the New Year Eve&apos;s bells in her town of Kyoto. Toshio is a successful author who made a name for himself by writing a novel based on the romance he had as a 30-year-old man with the young and passionate girl. An affair he had while his own wife was pregnant and expecting their first child. Otoko became pregnant as well, but lost</span>
  <span id="freeText10420663177864437147" style="display:none">Some 25 years after Toshio Oki's affair with then fifteen-year-old Otoko Ueno, Toshio, feeling nostalgic, decides to visit a now mature Otoko to listen to the ringing of the New Year Eve's bells in her town of Kyoto. Toshio is a successful author who made a name for himself by writing a novel based on the romance he had as a 30-year-old man with the young and passionate girl. An affair he had while his own wife was pregnant and expecting their first child. Otoko became pregnant as well, but lost the baby shortly after giving birth to a little girl. Otoko is now a reclusive artist living with her protégée and young lover, Keiko, a young girl gifted with talent as an artist in her own right, and a sharp taste for vengeance. When he meets the two women together for the New Year Eve event, Keiko decides she will avenge her mistress and begins a manipulative game, which ensnares both Toshio and his son Taichiro. <br /><br />Comparisons to Lolita are almost inevitable because of the man-child relationship, but the similarity ends there. The events take place decades after the relationship has ended and young Keiko and her passion for retribution take over. <br /><br />I've been meaning to read this novel and other Kawabata works for many years now, and I can't say whether it was the subject matter of a mature man having relations with a teenager that made me uncomfortable (of course it did), or the fact I listened to this instead of eye-reading it. The writing is apparently one of the attractions of this Nobel laureate's novels, but it was lost on me here, and I was only able to focus on the rather sordid story. It was good, but not a memorable experience. I'll definitely be reading his other books in print or ebook format to give myself a chance to enjoy the prose next time, albeit in translation. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10420663177864437147" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


