    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2882770494" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2882770494" />
    <a title="Mizuki" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16842102-mizuki"><img alt="Mizuki" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1368277474p2/16842102.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2882770494?book_show_action=true">Jul 28, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mizuki" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mizuki" href="/user/show/16842102-mizuki">Mizuki</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2882770494" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6720595728600817797">2.5 stars.<br/><br/>The famed Japanese novelist Yasunari Kawabata wrote many novels which focused mostly on the beauty of Japanese traditional cultures, the scenery and the relationship between men and women, and his novels are often a &apos;hit or miss&apos; for me.<br/><br/>After enjoying his elegantly written novels such as <i>The Old Capitol</i>, <i>Snow Country</i> and <i>Sleeping Beauties</i>; <i>Beauty and Sadness</i> really feels like a miss to me.<br/><br/>Once again, the backdrop is set in Koyto, though it&apos;s interesting to see how Mr. Kawabata describe</span>
  <span id="freeText6720595728600817797" style="display:none">2.5 stars.<br /><br />The famed Japanese novelist Yasunari Kawabata wrote many novels which focused mostly on the beauty of Japanese traditional cultures, the scenery and the relationship between men and women, and his novels are often a 'hit or miss' for me.<br /><br />After enjoying his elegantly written novels such as <i>The Old Capitol</i>, <i>Snow Country</i> and <i>Sleeping Beauties</i>; <i>Beauty and Sadness</i> really feels like a miss to me.<br /><br />Once again, the backdrop is set in Koyto, though it's interesting to see how Mr. Kawabata described the ancient city, still the male lead of the story is an asshole no matter how you look at it. I know fictional characters don't have to be role models or saints but I don't have anything to root for such a character at all. I know Mr. Kawabata's male characters are always a bit on the asshole-ish side but this time a male lead who had impregnated a 17 years old girl while he was already married by that time really is crossing the line. (Plus this male lead also happens to be a novelist, ha!)<br /><br />The male lead's wife and how she was jealous of her husband's younger mistress is mentioned in passing but hardly anything comes out of it.<br /><br />The only interesting part is the painter (who was once the male lead's young mistress years ago) and her pupil and the homosexual relationship between them. It's rumored that said relationship between the two women is inspired by Mr. Kawabata's relationship with a male friend. However, neither the painter nor the pupil have much in-depth insight to offer when art and female's sensuality is concerned. <br /><br />If you have a lot of patience, you can try this book out,I guess.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6720595728600817797" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

