<div id="review_3516636098" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3516636098" />
    <a title="Taruna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/20403981-taruna"><img alt="Taruna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1545486256p2/20403981.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3516636098?book_show_action=true">Sep 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Taruna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Taruna" href="/user/show/20403981-taruna">Taruna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141192611" href="/book/show/9248070-beauty-and-sadness">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3516636098" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4268014915147934433">What a beautiful book. It always amazes me how people are capable of writing about the most ambiguous of feelings so well. I myself am a person who often falls prey to nametags to understand people and myself, but it is books such as these that remind me just how complex human emotions and feelings are. Earlier this year, I had a similar experience reading Milan Kundera’s the unbearable lightness of being.<br/><br/>The writing is so elegant and poignant, its delicacy also reminded me of James Baldwin’s Gi</span>
  <span id="freeText4268014915147934433" style="display:none">What a beautiful book. It always amazes me how people are capable of writing about the most ambiguous of feelings so well. I myself am a person who often falls prey to nametags to understand people and myself, but it is books such as these that remind me just how complex human emotions and feelings are. Earlier this year, I had a similar experience reading Milan Kundera’s the unbearable lightness of being.<br /><br />The writing is so elegant and poignant, its delicacy also reminded me of James Baldwin’s Giovanni’s room. One can feel a sense of nostalgia throughout the book, as well as a deep admiration for Japanese history, art, culture and landscape. Beautiful descriptions of nature, loss and suffering. I especially loved Keiko’s character - bold, unapologetic but so fragile and insecure. <br /><br />I was very uncomfortable with the premise (30 year old man Oki gets a 15 year old girl Otoko pregnant while he has a wife) and a certain disgust with Oki remained with me throughout the book. Otoko’s supposed love for him that still remains after 2 decades can be seen in so many lights - trauma, longing, delusion, a sort of ignorance of having been violated. The writing again is so poignant and truthful that one does not judge her for loving the man, instead sees through her. <br /><br />There was something about the feeling of this book that seemed to spread a quiet around me. I wish I had finished it in one or two sittings. I would definitely recommend it to anyone interested in understanding complex emotions, Japanese aesthetics, nostalgic books. And also to sit through it in one go to really feel its immensity. <br /><br />Definitely looking forward to read more of Kawabata</span>
  <a data-text-id="4268014915147934433" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


