<span id="freeTextContainer9599282874060979287">So. A friend told me, “don’t try to make too much sense from the book.” I tried to keep her wise advice in mind and that’s what kept me going through this strange book. <br/><br/>That and the fact that there were glorious descriptions of Kyoto, one of my favorite cities, bringing back warm memories of my visit there. But most of the characters behave in strange fashion, as the friend wrote, “there’s a touch of madness” in all of them. Oh well, aren’t we all?<br/><br/>I think the book makes more sense to me as an un</span>
  <span id="freeText9599282874060979287" style="display:none">So. A friend told me, “don’t try to make too much sense from the book.” I tried to keep her wise advice in mind and that’s what kept me going through this strange book. <br /><br />That and the fact that there were glorious descriptions of Kyoto, one of my favorite cities, bringing back warm memories of my visit there. But most of the characters behave in strange fashion, as the friend wrote, “there’s a touch of madness” in all of them. Oh well, aren’t we all?<br /><br />I think the book makes more sense to me as an understanding of the human psyche rather than an enjoyable book in itself. I can probably sit with a cup of tea and ruminate over each of the character’s actions. And that might be far more pleasing than the time I spent reading the book.</span>
